  "opinion": "As a retired woman from Bari who spent her early years in a small Italian town, I’ve seen how science has always been a field where men dominate, but it’s not just about numbers—it’s about the stories we tell ourselves. Growing up, my parents didn’t have much education, but they taught me to look at the world with curiosity, which is what led me to photography and birdwatching. I remember sitting by the river with my father, pointing out stars and asking why the sky was blue. That sense of wonder is what drives many in science, yet it’s often overshadowed by societal expectations. The gender gap in science isn’t just about fewer women in labs—it’s about the cultural narratives that tell girls they’re not ‘good’ at math or physics. I’ve noticed that in my community, even among older women, there’s a quiet belief that science is for boys. This isn’t a new problem; it’s been there since the days when women couldn’t even attend university. But addressing it isn’t about pushing for more women in labs—it’s about changing how we see science itself. We need to create spaces where curiosity isn’t tied to gender, where girls can explore without fear of judgment. For example, in my town, we’ve started a small science club for kids where both boys and girls work together on projects. It’s simple, but it’s powerful. The key is to stop treating science as a competition between genders and start seeing it as a shared journey of discovery. The gap isn’t a barrier—it’s a reflection of how we’ve shaped our world. And we can fix it by starting with the stories we tell ourselves.",
